Martin van Cleve discussed at length by Marlier Pierre Bruegel le Jeune, special chapter on M. van Cleve, pp. 333ff, but also elsewhere in the book. The copy, by P.B.II 1630, in Stockholm of Peasant couple attacked by Soldiers, Martin p. 275, fig. 162 which is generally believed to be based on a lost P.B.I, may actually go back, I think, to an original by M. van Cleve.

column4: <content>Martin van Cleve discussed at length by Marlier Pierre Bruegel le Jeune, special chapter on M. van Cleve, pp. 333ff, but also elsewhere in the book. The copy, by P.B.II 1630, in Stockholm of Peasant couple attacked by Soldiers, Martin p. 275, fig. 162 which is generally believed to be based on a lost P.B.I, may actually go back, I think, to an original by M. van Cleve.</content>
